responses.Q4:
Cardiovascular disease is currently the leading causes of death in the United States. The goal of my research is to identify and functionally characterize genes contributing to cardiovascular disease in order to ultimately translate genetic discoveries into individualized patient care through pharmacogenomics and/or other clinical approaches.

Aspirin and clopidogrel therapy significantly improves cardiovascular outcomes in patients with various coronary syndromes by inhibiting platelet function. However, variable inter-individual responses to anti-platelet therapies exist resulting in increased risk of recurrent cardiovascular events in some patients. My objective is to identify genetic variants through candidate gene studies, genome-wide association analyses, and other "omics" approaches that contribute to differences in platelet response and to functionally elucidate the molecular mechanisms responsible for this variability. Studies in my laboratory have shown that genetic variants in the Platelet Endothelial Aggregation Receptor 1 (PEAR1) gene are associated with platelet reactivity and cardiovascular outcomes in patients on aspirin therapy. We are currently exploring further the functional consequences of these polymorphisms in cellular models as well as in human populations. In addition, potential pharmacogenetic effects of paraoxonase 1 (PON1), carboxyesterase 1 (CES1), and ATP-binding cassette sub-family C member 4 (ABCC4) on clopidogrel efficacy are currently being investigated.

responses.Q4: Dr. Fullertons work focuses on the ethical and social implications of genetics and genomics research, including researcher and participant perspectives on data-sharing, secondary use, and result return. responses.Q4: The Sadee group studies the genetics and genomics of complex common diseases and therapies, as an integral part of the OSU Program in Pharmacogenomics.  Research studies focus on the genetics of drug metabolizing enzymes, membrane transporters and drug targets/receptors, and in addition genetic factors determining disease susceptibility  relevant to guiding personalized therapy.  Advances in our understanding of interindividual variability indicate that regulatory polymorphisms outweigh those that affect directly the protein coding sequence, but a vast majority of such variants remains to be discovered.  A main approach of the molecular genetics work entails expression genetics, i.e., the study of polymorphisms and epigenetic factors determining.  , the Sadee laboratory has discovered frequent regulatory variants in key genes, including OPRM1, DRD2, MDR1, ACE, TPH2, MAOA, CYP3A4, CYP2D6.  Use of large scale data analytics, these variants has subsequently demonstrated associations with clinical phenotypes, involving cardiovascular and CNS disorders, addiction, and other complex disorders.  A main goal is to develop predictive biomarkers.

responses.Q4: My research focuses on the application of pharmacogenetic and pharmacogenomic strategies to characterize the relative contributions of ontogeny, genetic variation, and disease to observed variability in drug disposition and response in children.  Specifically, I have had a longstanding interest in applying these principles to individualize drug therapy in children, with a particular focus on CYP2D6.  Achievements in this area stem from a particularly productive partnership with Andrea Gaedigk, PhD and her expertise related to CYP2D6 gene structure and genotyping strategies together with my interest in in vivo phenotype assessment.  Among our contributions in this area, perhaps the most significant has been development of the CYP2D6 "Activity Score", to provide a semiquantitative phenotype assignment from genotype data, which has been widely accepted.  Our group also provided genotyping expertise for the index case of fatal morphine toxicity in a breastfed neonate of a mother using codeine that subsequently resulted in a black-box warning being added to the codeine label in the US, Canada and the UK.   Recognizing that genotype-phenotype associations will only be observed in children once the gene is fully expressed (e.g., infants may be phenotypically "poor metabolizers" if expression of the gene is low or absent for developmental reasons), knowledge of when the gene is mature (ontogeny) is essential.  Therefore, we have been very active in developing strategies to characterize drug biotransformation in vivo, based on metabolite profiles in urine.  For example, we have conducted several longitudinal phenotyping studies in pediatric populations of different ages and have demonstrated that CYP2D6 phenotype is concordant with genotype by 2 weeks of age in full term infants; my currently funded R01 investigates the change in phenotype during puberty.  Urinary metabolite profiling is also being applied to investigate reactive metabolite formation in children.  Overall, our various in vivo investigations have also emphasized the importance of understanding the underlying developmental context to properly interpret pharmacogenetic data and drug responses in children.

responses.Q4: I am a medical oncologist and clinical pharmacologist in the Department of Medicine, Section of Hematology/Oncology at the University of Chicago. As a clinician, I see patients in the Gastrointestinal Oncology Clinic and the Developmental Therapeutics Clinic (phase I program). I am the principal investigator on numerous clinical trials for gastrointestinal and advanced solid malignancies, with a focus on repurposing of older drugs, combination and drug-drug interaction studies, pharmacogenomics, food effect studies, first-in-human studies, unique trial designs/endpoints, and pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic modeling. I also conduct research involving the use of longitudinal data from completed oncology clinical trials to develop disease progression models of biomarkers and patient reported outcomes. The broad objective of this research is to improve the development and use of oncology therapeutics, and I developed my skills in this area by receiving a masters degree in pharmacometrics from the University of Maryland  Baltimore. Currently, I have a Translational Scholar Award in Pharmacogenomics and Personalized Medicine (K23) entitled Genomic prediction tools developed using phenotypes from disease progression models for this work. I am also an active member of the Population Pharmacology and Pharmacogenomics committee of the Alliance for Clinical Trials in Oncology, and the Clinical Trial Design Task Force of the Investigational Drug Steering Committee. At the institutional level, I serve as the chair of the Oncology Drug Safety Committee and the Associate Director of the Committee on Clinical Pharmacology and Pharmacogenomics, the latter of which includes a training program for fellows.

responses.Q4: My research activities have focused on pharmacogenomics of anticancer agent toxicity.  I have developed cell-based methods to identify genetic variants contributing to chemotherapeutic induced cytotoxicity that can be studied in a clinical setting. My laboratory was the first to demonstrate that chemotherapeutic induced cytotoxicity is a heritable trait and that pharmacologic GWAS SNPs are enriched in expression quantitative trait loci.  More recently, my laboratory has extended our HapMap cell-based model to develop an induced pluripotent stem cell derived neuronal cell model to evaluate chemotherapeutic induced neuropathy, the most common non-hematologic adverse event of multiple chemotherapeutic agents. This toxicity presents a quality of life issue, since the pain and disability may be permanent, and it is a common reason a chemotherapy regimen is dose reduced or permanently stopped early, which may have an impact on survival. The iPSC derived sensory neurons allow us to: a) study peripheral neuropathy in genetically diverse human sensory neurons in ways that were not possible previously; b) gain insight on druggable targets to treat or prevent this devastating side effect of chemotherapy; c) provide an understanding of the genetic components and genes contributing to severe toxicity; d) provide a human cellular model that can be used for screening of drugs to determine if they are neurotoxic.

responses.Q4: Vicki L. Ellingrod, Pharm.D., FCCP, is The John Gideon Searle Professor of Clinical and Translational Psychiatry in the Clinical, Social, and Administrative Sciences Department in the College of Pharmacy and a professor of psychiatry in the Department of Psychiatry in the School of Medicine. In addition, she serves as director of the Clinical Pharmacogenomics Laboratory at the University of Michigan. From 1994 to 1996, she completed a postdoctoral fellowship in psychopharmacology/pharmacogenetics at the University of Iowa and then joined the faculty in 1996 as an assistant professor. There, she completed a K08 training grant funded by NIMH (National Institute of Mental Health). In 2006, she joined the faculty at the University of Michigan. Her research has primarily been funded by the NIMH and focuses on the pharmacogenomics of mental health treatment. Dr. Ellingrod also serves as a scientific editor for Pharmacotherapy.

NIH R01 R01 MH082784-S1 (Ellingrod)	06/01/14-05/31/15
Role: Principal Investigator
Antipsychotic and Folate Pharmacogenetics  gender supplement
The goal of this study is to identify epigenome profile differences in race, age and folate status matched males and female subjects stratified by a metabolic syndrome diagnosis and to determine gene-specific methylation differences associated with gender and metabolic syndrome in schizophrenia subjects.  

NIMH R01 MH082784-W2 (Ellingrod)	08/01/14-07/31/15
Role: Principal Investigator
Antipsychotic and Folate Pharmacogenetics  metabolomics supplement
The goal of this study is to add a unique metabolite read-out to the clinical and genetic risk factors for metabolic syndrome risk in schizophrenia patients receiving atypical antipsychotics (AAPs) currently being investigated in the parent R01. This supplement will inform the future directions of the current MH082784 application as we apply the knowledge obtained from this supplement and the identified metabolic signatures related to metabolic risk in our highly phenotyped patients at risk for significant cardiovascular disease (CVD). 

NIMH R01MH082784 (Ellingrod)	7/22/2013-6/30/2018
Role: Principal Investigator
Antipsychotic and Folate Pharmacogenetics
The goal of this study is to examine folate pharmacogenomics in relation to metabolic syndrome, insulin resistance, and endothelial dysfunction from atypical antipsychotic use in schizophrenia and to determine the utility of folate supplementation in attenuation of these complications.

responses.Q4: My overall research goals are to investigate genetic causes of response and side effects to psychiatric medications. This line of research aims to significantly improve treatment of psychiatric conditions and to lessen the burden of medication side effects and to avoid negative drug-drug interactions. In addition, I am actively involved in developing pharmacogenetic guidelines for physicians and patients through my affiliations with the Clinical Pharmacogenetics Implementation Consortium (Caudle KE et. al, 2014) as well to develop implementation models of pharmacogenetics in clinical practice (e.g., Mller DJ et al., 2013).
